Introduction

For this project, our group decided on the topic of board games. Although we are all generally familar with board games through personal experience, we realized that we know very little about the data-driven factors that influence popularity, game ratings, and long-term success of each board game. Essentially, we wanted to learn more about their popularity and how they compare to one another. In addition, we wanted to explore what specific factors drive engagement with board games.

In this day and age, children tend to gravitate more towards TV and video games. In general, traditional tabletop games have been facing growing competition from television, mobile apps, and video games. According to a National Library of Medicine publication, video games have a global market of 150 billion dollars, while board games have a global market of only 7 billion dollars. Thus, by analyzing a dataset of board games, we hope to uncover what makes board games appealing and how these insights can be used to strengthen the way they're marketed and sold!

Furthermore, from a data-science perspective, this dataset will give us a great opportunity to practice exploratory analysis, visualization-making, feature-interpreting, and a variety of research techniques!

Data curation

For this project, we chose a dataset from the Kaggle website that contains board game information scraped from BoardGameGeek (BGG), the world's largest board game database.

The dataset includes information on game specifications, user ratings, popularity metrics, designer credits, and real-time marketplace pricing for games available on Amazon.

Additionally, this dataset is also a reasonable size, with 2000 rows and 57 columns. This means that there will be plenty of data to dissect and review for this project!

Just like any other Python project, we need to import some libraries. Below are some of the libraries we will be using throughout this project.

One of the main libraries we use throughout this project is Pandas. It is a powerful Python library for data manipulation and analysis. It provides easy-to-use tools for working with structured data, such as DataFrames and Series, allowing you to clean, transform, filter, group, and analyze datasets efficiently.

Hypothesis Testing

In the price vs. rating scatterplot, you can likely to see a trend between the two features. In order to test out this thought, we undergo hypothesis testing.

Hypothesis testing is a statistical method used to make decisions or draw conclusions about a population based on sample data. The null hypothesis is the baseline assumption that there is no relationship between two features. The alternative hypothesis is what we want to investigate, which states that there is a relationship between the two features.

For more information on how hypothesis testing works, visit this website.

Null Hypothesis: The price of a games does not have a relationship to the average rating.

Alternative Hypothesis: The price of a game has a relationship to the average rating.

Significance Level: 0.01

In[94]:
square  = scipy.stats.linregress(no_outliers["amazon_price"], no_outliers["avg_rating"])
print("Correlation",square.rvalue)
print("Pvalue", square.pvalue)

Correlation 0.4249269406732697
Pvalue 5.06241808100707e-47

In this situation we reject the null hypothis that the price of a game does not have a relationship to the rating as our p value is 1.2e-44 which is much less than our significance level of 0.01. This means that the price of a game does have a relationship to the average rating. In addion because our corrolation value is positive we can see that with out current data the more a game costs the higher it will be rated.

Feature Correlation Analysis

Now that we've established correlation between price and rating, let's observe the relationships between other features in the dataset!

A good way to do this is through feature correlation analysis, and specifically creating a correlation heatmap to easily view relationships.

Darker squares demonstrate strong positive correlations, which mean that as one feature increases, the other also tends to increase.

Lighter squares demonstrate strong negative correlations, which mean that as one feature increases, the other tends to decrease.

As you can see below, there is a strong correlation (darker square) between the number of ratings and features related to popularity or engagement.

Overall, this type of visualization can help us to identify key factors that might influence a board game's popularity, rating, or other characteristics.

Predicting Amazon Price

Based on the structure of the dataset and the relationships observed in our exploratory plots, we selected regression as our primary modeling technique for predicting Amazon price. The target variable, Amazon price, is a continuous numeric value, making regression a natural fit. Many of the features we examined (complexity, number of ratings, fans, total plays, and playtime) are also numerical and show potential relationships with price. For example, games with higher complexity or higher engagement metrics often appear to be priced higher. To explore this further, we extended our analysis to examine the broader question:

Which game attributes most strongly predict a board game's Amazon price?

To answer this, we fit several regression models using a diverse set of predictors, compare their performance, and assess which features contribute most to price variation.

We start by selecting numeric features related to complexity, popularity, playtime, and release year, then extract them along with the target variable. All columns are converted to numeric to avoid formatting issues, and any rows with missing values are removed. The resulting cleaned DataFrame (df_price) is ready for use in the regression analysis.

First, the feature matrix (X) and target variable (y) are defined. We then divide the data so that 80% is used to train the regression model and 20% is reserved for testing its performance. Because the predictors vary widely in scale, a StandardScaler is applied to normalize them, ensuring that no single feature heavily influences the model. The result is a set of scaled training and testing inputs ready for regression.

Four different algorithms are initialized: Linear Regression, K-Nearest Neighbors, a Decision Tree, and a Random Forest.

In[99]:
models = {
    "Linear Regression": LinearRegression(),

    "Decision Tree": DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=42),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)
}

We use KFold to randomly divide the training data into five parts. For each model, cross_val_score computes the R score across all folds, and the average and standard deviation are printed to help identify which algorithm generalizes best.

In[100]:
kf = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

for name, model in models.items():
    scores = cross_val_score(
        model,
        X_train_scaled,
        y_train,
        scoring="r2",
        cv=kf
    )
    print(f"{name}: Mean R = {scores.mean():.4f} (+/- {scores.std():.4f})")

Linear Regression: Mean R = 0.1790 (+/- 0.0715)
KNN Regressor: Mean R = 0.1254 (+/- 0.1269)
Decision Tree: Mean R = -0.5571 (+/- 0.5260)
Random Forest: Mean R = 0.0534 (+/- 0.1980)

The cross-validation results indicate that predicting a board game's Amazon price is challenging using the selected features. Among the models tested, Linear Regression performed best, explaining only about 18% of the variation in price, while KNN and Random Forest showed weaker and less consistent performance. The Decision Tree performed very poorly, with a negative R, indicating it overfits the training data and fails to generalize. Overall, these results suggest that features like complexity, number of ratings, fans, and total plays capture only a small portion of what influences a game's market price, and other factors may be necessary to better predict price.

Linear Regression had the highest mean R among the models tested, so we train a Linear Regression model on the scaled training data to predict Amazon price. After fitting the model, it generates predictions for the test set, which can be used to evaluate how well the model estimates game prices. The magnitude of the models coefficients also provides insight into which features have the strongest influence on price.

Predicting the Rating of and Price Range in Future Years

For second part of our primary analysis, we took various price ranges in increments of ten dollars and then trained a model using the increase in ratings over time to predict the rating in future years for the given price range.

df_y['release_year'] = df_y['release_year'] - 1950 # Make data smaller and easier to work with
df_y = df_y[vars].dropna()

# Setup X and Y vars for analysis
X_vars = ["release_year"]
Y_vars = ['avg_rating']
In[104]:
class BestModel:
  def __init__(self, data, graph, a):
    self.a = a # The number for the range
    # Variables
    self.X = data[X_vars]
    self.Y = data[Y_vars]

    # Graph stuff
    self.ax = graph
    self.ax.scatter(self.X+1950,self.Y)
    self.ax.set_xlabel("release_year")
    self.ax.set_ylabel("avg_rating")

    # Scale the X and Y Variables
    self.scaler_x = StandardScaler()
    self.X_scaled = self.scaler_x.fit_transform(self.X)

    self.scaler_y = StandardScaler()
    self.Y_scaled = self.scaler_y.fit_transform(self.Y).squeeze()

    # The models to use
    self.models = { "KNN": KNeighborsRegressor(),
            "DecisionTree": DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state = seed),
            "LinearRegression": LinearRegression(),
            "RandomForest": RandomForestRegressor(random_state = seed)
    }
  def find_best_model(self):
    # Perform k-fold Cross-Validation for each model
    k_folds = 5
    kf = KFold(n_splits=k_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=seed)

    max_score = -np.inf
    max_model = ""

    for model_name, model in self.models.items():

        # Test to find the best
        cv_scores = cross_val_score(
            model,
            self.X_scaled,
            self.Y_scaled.squeeze(),
            cv=kf,
            scoring='r2'
        )
        # Check what the highest scoring model is and return it
        score = cv_scores.mean()
        if score  > max_score:
          max_score = score
          max_model = model_name

    self.models[max_model].fit(self.X_scaled, self.Y_scaled) # X Scaled

    # Find the linear regression line if its the best model
    if max_model=="LinearRegression":
      self.graph_linear_regresion(model=self.models[max_model])

    # Setup the grapj
    self.ax.set_title(f"\\${self.a*10}-\\${(self.a+1)*10} using {max_model}")
    self.ax.set_xlabel("Year")
    self.ax.set_ylabel("Rating")

    # Return all of the objects
    return ({"model":self.models[max_model],"num":self.a,"scaler_x":self.scaler_x, "scaler_y":self.scaler_y})

  def graph_linear_regresion(self,model):
    # ----- Pick ONE feature to plot (e.g., the first column) -----
    x_feature_train = self.X.iloc[:, 0]          # unscaled feature
    x_feature_scaled = self.X_scaled[:, 0]       # scaled version

    # Predict on the scaled feature
    y_pred_scaled = model.predict(x_feature_scaled.reshape(-1, 1))
    y_pred = self.scaler_y.inverse_transform(y_pred_scaled.reshape(-1,1))

    # Sort by the feature value for a smooth line
    sorted_idx = x_feature_train.argsort()

    # Plot regression line
    self.ax.plot(
        x_feature_train.iloc[sorted_idx]+1950,
        y_pred[sorted_idx],
        linewidth=4,
        label="Regression Line",
        color="green"
    )

  # Exit loop if there is not enough data for that range
  if data.empty or len(data)<=10:
    continue
  find_best = BestModel(data,graph=ax,a=a )
  predictors.append(find_best.find_best_model())

  df_final[name] = info["scaler_y"].inverse_transform(predicted_scaled.reshape(1, -1))[0]

  # Plot the line of the results
  ax1.plot(df_final['Year'], df_final[name], label = name.replace("$","\\$"))

# Setup the overall plot
ax1.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', borderaxespad=0.)
ax1.set_xlabel("Year")
ax1.set_ylabel("Rating")
ax1.set_title("Rating Predicted Over Time for Various Price Ranges")
ax1.set_ylim(0,10)

# Make a copy for zoomed in view
fig2, ax2 = plt.subplots()

for line in ax1.get_lines():
    ax2.plot(line.get_xdata(),line.get_ydata(),label= line.get_label())
ax2.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', borderaxespad=0.)
ax2.set_xlabel("Year")
ax2.set_ylabel("Rating")
ax2.set_ylim(5.5,9.5)
ax2.set_title("Rating Predicted Over Time for Various Price Ranges(Y Zoomed)")
plt.show()

years_to_display = [2010,2020,2030,2040]

Insights and Conclusions

Now, to tie it all together, let's talk about what we got out of our data analysis. Through our exploration and analysis of this board game dataset, we were able to gain many valuable insights about various board games' popularity, ratings, pricing, and long-term success as a whole.

Based on the hypothesis testing, where the p-value was less than the significance value of 0.01, representing a statistically significant positive relationship between price and rating, we rejected the null hypothesis that there is no correlation between the two metrics. Based on the correlation value we got, which is positive, we can also say that the higher the price of a game, the higher its rating is.

The feature correlation analysis allowed us to use a correlation heatmap to visualize various relationships and their strengths. Based on this correlation heatmap that we generated, it is evident that the number of ratings feature is often strongly correlated to features that represent popularity or engagement for the board game, such as wishlisted, fans, comments, and previously owned. This means that the higher the number of ratings is, the more popular the board games tend to be, considering there are a higher number of things like comments and ownership.

For the primary analysis that we used regression to complete, we were aiming to best predict the Amazon price of a game and distinguish which attributes of a board game most strongly and accurately predict the board game's price on Amazon. The features that we evaluated using various regression models were related to complexity, popularity, playtime, and release data. After cleaning, splitting, and generating the models, the cross-validation results that we got indicated that it was difficult to accurately predict a board game's Amazon price based solely on the features that we selected. However, based on the Linear Regression model and bar chart, we saw that the number of fans and average rating of a board game were the two most important for predicting the Amazon price. This insight tells us that the number of fans a board game has and the average rating of a board game are the most important features in being able to predict the board game's prices. Analyzing this relationship, we can see how the two features relate to each other becuase a higher number of fans will generally mean a higher average rating. Since there are more people who like the game and prices are often based on market demand, the more people who like the game, the higher the rating will be, so it is likely that the price will also be higher since there is a larger number of people who want the game.

In the second part of our primary analysis, we took various price ranges in increments of ten dollars and then used the increase in ratings over time to predict the average rating in future years for the given price range. For this, we tested different regression models and used the best-performing model for the prediction shown in the graphs. Based on these graphs, we are able to identify that over time, ratings tend to increase, which could be due to the board game being on the market for longer.

Overall, our analysis suggests that board game success, defined by higher ratings and more popularity, is driven not so much by mechanical/technical factors such as complexity, playtime, or release date, but rather more so by engagement, as even perceived value. Despite higher-priced games also having high average ratings based on our regression analysis, the number of fans actually proved to be the most important feature in predicting board game prices. Although our primary analysis revealed that it is difficult to predict prices solely based on complexity, popularity, playtime, and release year, it still highlighted that long-term success in the board game market is tied most closely to the engagement of the game. This means that for board game developers, rather than trying to build complex, time-consuming games, they should focus on ideas that will resonate with a wide audience and have a high perceived value, not just for a few years but long-term, maintaining an essentially timeless relevance.
